*"But here is where we irrevocably part: **Your framework still treats inherent value as *contingent* on ecological function—not as an intrinsic property of ‘subjects-of-a-life*.** As I argue in *The Case for Animal Rights*, any being with beliefs, desires, perception, memory, sense of future, emotional life, and an individual welfare *possesses inherent value that cannot be overridden by utilitarian calculations, ecological benefits, or systemic ‘resilience’*. Your ESF permits treating such beings as *means* to boundary adherence—precisely what the rights view forbids. Let me show why, using your own structure against itself."*  

