*Why Regan insists:* Innovation is just one source of rights violations. Policies (e.g., subsidies for animal ag), cultural practices (e.g., festive slaughter), and even boundary-enforcement actions (e.g., culling invasive species) must pass this test. The IVIA mirrors environmental impact statements—but for inherent value.  

#### **3. Revise Dynamic Knowledge (Pillar 3): Rights Literacy as Core Competency**  
> **Current Pillar 3**: Dynamic Knowledge (includes epistemic humility, knowledge pluralism)  
> **Regan’s Revision**: ***Dynamic Knowledge & Rights Literacy***  
> *Truth is provisional. Wisdom arises from integrating knowledge *with rights-aware reasoning*—weighing inherent value equally across subjects-of-a-life.*  
> **Non-Negotiable Practices**:  
