In the end, Regan wouldn’t see the ESF as “too absolutist”—he’d see it as a framework that *finally* takes inherent value seriously: **that subjects-of-a-life aren’t here for our use.** And that, he’d say quietly, is worth fighting for—because as he writes in *The Case for Animal Rights*: *“To treat a being as a mere means is to fail to respect its inherent value—and inherent value is not something that can be balanced against other values. It is the ground of all value.”*  

