>- *In your food system redesign (Section II), you praise regenerative agriculture—but you don’t see how it *still risks instrumentalizing life*: manure from confined hens, slaughterhouse byproducts as fertilizer, or ‘holistic grazing’ that treats cattle as ‘tools’ for soil carbon. When we use a cow’s body to ‘build soil,’ we have already forgotten that she is a mother who grieves her stolen calf, a creature who lows for companionship, a being whose life is not a means to our ends.*  
>- *In your self-critique (Section IV), you note the poorest bear transition costs—but you don’t see how *true stewardship* would begin not with ‘alternatives delivered first’ but with *repentance*: acknowledging that we have treated the creature as a thing, and that our ecological crises are, in part, a symptom of that spiritual estrangement.*  
