*In *Dominion*, I show how the dominion mandate is not a warrant for use but a call to *imitate God’s own care*: He ‘makes the grass grow for the cattle, and plants for man to cultivate’ (Psalm 104:14)—not so we may exploit, but so we may *participate* in the divine economy of generosity. Your framework risks reducing stewardship to a *technical fix*—weighing gains against losses—when it should be a *moral awakening*: **What kind of people do we wish to be when we look into the eyes of the creature we hold power over?**"*  

